(159, 1, '2014-06-29 03:40:58', '2014-06-29 03:40:58', '<b>San Francisco Neighborhood Centers Together (SFNCT) is a network for the City''s Neighborhood Centers. </b>We work with our members to build capacity through peer support, coaching, and training. We share resources, information, and best practices with our members, stakeholders, local government, and funders.\r\n<b>\r\n</b> Neighborhood Centers are anchor institutions that provide programs and services, and build connections between residents, community and neighborhood groups, schools, faith-based groups, merchants, and local public agencies.<b>\r\n</b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\ngggggggg', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '53-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-29 03:40:58', '2014-06-29 03:40:58', '', 53, 'http://localhost:8888/sfnct/53-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(160, 1, '2014-06-30 15:26:17', '2014-06-30 15:26:17', '<b>San Francisco Neighborhood Centers Together (SFNCT) is a network for the City''s Neighborhood Centers. </b>We work with our members to build capacity through peer support, coaching, and training. We share resources, information, and best practices with our members, stakeholders, local government, and funders.\r\n<b>\r\n</b> Neighborhood Centers are anchor institutions that provide programs and services, and build connections between residents, community and neighborhood groups, schools, faith-based groups, merchants, and local public agencies.<b></b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '53-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-30 15:26:17', '2014-06-30 15:26:17', '', 53, 'http://localhost:8888/sfnct/53-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(161, 1, '2014-07-08 14:45:46', '2014-07-08 14:45:46', '<a name="WhatWeDo"><strong>What we Do</strong></a>\n\n<a href="https://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/about_us.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-103" src="https://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/about_us.jpg" alt="about_us" width="300" height="203" /></a>\n\nSFNCT came together in 2001 through the initiative and support of the San Francisco Mayor''s Office of Community Development (MOCD), which is now the Mayor''s Office of Housing, Community Development Division.\n\nFormer MOCD Director Pamela David recognized the value and importance of the Neighborhood Centers. She also recognized the challenges faced by these anchor institutions in the form of categorical funding that did not support their essential community building and community organizing work. Ms. David convened a meeting for Executive Directors of Neighborhood Centers to discuss ways for MOCD to support their leaders and their work.\n\nThe group continued to meet, building strong connections between the Neighborhood Centers, and between these agencies and MOCD. In late 2001 Executive Directors of the participating agencies, with the support of MOCD, launched San Francisco Neighborhood Centers Together to:\n<ul>\n  <li>Advocate for the Neighborhood Center/Settlement House model as an effective solution for addressing social and economic issues</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n  <li>Build and strengthen connections between Neighborhood Centers</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n <li>Increase dialogue between the Neighborhood Centers and City officials</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n <li>Design and implement collaborative projects</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n <li>Share information, resources, and "back-office" services</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n  <li>Provide peer mentoring and support for Neighborhood Center leaders</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n  <li>Facilitate successful leadership transitions</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n  <li>Communicate the value, impact, and accomplishments of the Neighborhood Centers to funders, stakeholders, and City officials</li>\n</ul>\n\n<a name="WhatWeDo"><strong>What we Do</strong></a>\n\nSFNCT members have been collaborating, sharing services, and building agency, individual, and community capacity since our founding as a network in 2001.\n\n&nbsp;', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '66-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-07-08 14:45:46', '2014-07-08 14:45:46', '', 66, 'http://localhost:8888/sfnct/66-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(162, 1, '2014-06-30 22:12:57', '2014-06-30 22:12:57', '<a href="https://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/about_us.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-103" src="https://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/about_us.jpg" alt="about_us" width="300" height="203" /></a>\r\n\r\nSFNCT came together in 2001 through the initiative and support of the San Francisco Mayor''s Office of Community Development (MOCD), which is now the Mayor''s Office of Housing, Community Development Division.\r\n\r\nFormer MOCD Director Pamela David recognized the value and importance of the Neighborhood Centers. She also recognized the challenges faced by these anchor institutions in the form of categorical funding that did not support their essential community building and community organizing work. Ms. David convened a meeting for Executive Directors of Neighborhood Centers to discuss ways for MOCD to support their leaders and their work.\r\n\r\nThe group continued to meet, building strong connections between the Neighborhood Centers, and between these agencies and MOCD. In late 2001 Executive Directors of the participating agencies, with the support of MOCD, launched San Francisco Neighborhood Centers Together to:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Advocate for the Neighborhood Center/Settlement House model as an effective solution for addressing social and economic issues</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Build and strengthen connections between Neighborhood Centers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Increase dialogue between the Neighborhood Centers and City officials</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Design and implement collaborative projects</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Share information, resources, and "back-office" services</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Provide peer mentoring and support for Neighborhood Center leaders</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Facilitate successful leadership transitions</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Communicate the value, impact, and accomplishments of the Neighborhood Centers to funders, stakeholders, and City officials</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSFNCT members have been collaborating, sharing services, and building agency, individual, and community capacity since our founding as a network in 2001.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '66-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-30 22:12:57', '2014-06-30 22:12:57', '', 66, 'http://localhost:8888/sfnct/66-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(163, 1, '2014-06-30 23:35:05', '2014-06-30 23:35:05', '<a href="hhttp://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/vision_and_mission.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-113" src="http://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/vision_and_mission-300x198.jpg" alt="vision_and_mission" width="300" height="198" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Vision</b>\r\nWe envision a San Francisco where the vibrancy and diversity of each neighborhood is celebrated and residents of all backgrounds are healthy and safe, with equal access to economic and social opportunities and creative fulfillment.\r\n\r\nAt the core of this vision are Neighborhood Centers addressing economic and social issues with local solutions; developing and strengthening community capacity; and building strong, healthy, safe and equitable neighborhoods.\r\n<b>\r\nMission</b>\r\nSFNCT strengthens and supports San Francisco’s Neighborhood Centers and the people who work in them. We fulfill our mission through capacity building and network building that achieves tangible results and benefits for our members and the people they serve.\r\n\r\nWe support our members through:\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Peer education and support</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Consultation, training, and coaching</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Information and resource sharing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Facilitation of shared "back-office" services</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Joint advocacy and resource development for SFNCT initiatives</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Ongoing dialogue and collaboration between SFNCT members, funders and stakeholders</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Advocacy for the Neighborhood Center model and the Neighborhood Centers</li>\r\n</ul>', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '69-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-30 23:35:05', '2014-06-30 23:35:05', '', 69, 'http://localhost:8888/sfnct/69-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(164, 1, '2014-06-30 23:35:33', '2014-06-30 23:35:33', '<center></center><a href="http://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/members.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-109" src="http://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/members-300x201.jpg" alt="members" width="300" height="201" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Our Members</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Bernal Heights Neighborhood Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Booker T. Washington Community Service Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Donaldina Cameron House</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Good Samaritan Family Resource Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>I.T. Bookman Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Mission Neighborhood Centers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Potrero Hill Neighborhood House</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li><i>Richmond District Neighborhood Center*</i></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Telegraph Hill Neighborhood Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n* <i>fiscal sponsor for SFNCT</i>\r\nSFNCT believes in a neighborhood-based, multi-service approach to improving the lives of City residents and the neighborhoods in which they live.\r\n\r\nOur members serve 30,000 people annually through programs, services, classes, community building, and community organizing initiatives, and hundreds of thousands of people annually through arts and cultural events. Neighborhood Centers identify and reinforce the strengths of individuals, families and communities. SFNCT members creatively and effectively address critical community needs in San Francisco’s diverse neighborhoods.\r\n\r\nNeighborhood Centers are multi-cultural, multi-generational, place-based organizations where everyone is welcome. They provide a safe space for dialogue and debate so people can come together to solve issues impacting their community. Our members own or control their facilities, giving them permanence and deep roots in their neighborhoods.<b>\r\n</b>\r\nSFNCT''s members are rooted in the history and values of the Settlement House movement. Settlement Houses originated in the late 1800s with the goal of promoting social and economic equity for new immigrants through education, social services, community organizing, and community building.', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '73-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-30 23:35:33', '2014-06-30 23:35:33', '', 73, 'http://localhost:8888/sfnct/73-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(165, 1, '2014-06-30 23:36:02', '2014-06-30 23:36:02', '<a href="http://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/funders.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-147" src="http://gbd.fwd.wf/sfnct/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/funders-300x201.jpg" alt="funders" width="300" height="201" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>SFNCT is grateful for the support of our funders:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Metta Fund</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>San Francisco Mayor''s Office of Housing, Community Development Division</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>The Whitman Institute</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Walter and Elise Haas Fund</li>\r\n</ul>', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '115-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-30 23:36:02', '2014-06-30 23:36:02', '', 115, 'http://localhost:8888/sfnct/115-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
